# Clerk auth and user data isolation

- **Authentication** is handled only by [Clerk](https://clerk.com/) (`@clerk/nextjs`: middleware, `ClerkProvider`, sign-in UI). Do not build parallel session systems or trust ad-hoc tokens for app authorization.

- **Authorization**: Users must only read or mutate rows that belong to them. Treat any ID from the client (URL params, body, headers) as an untrusted *selector*—never as proof of ownership.

## Server-side identity

- Resolve the actor with Clerk on the server (e.g. `auth()` from `@clerk/nextjs/server`). If there is no authenticated user, do not run owner-scoped queries; return **401** / redirect to the homepage (`/`) where the sign-in/sign-up buttons live as appropriate.

- Compare ownership using Clerk’s **`userId`** (e.g. `user_...`) against the database. In this project, **`decks.clerkUserId`** stores that value (see `src/db/schema.ts`).

## Queries (Drizzle)

- **Top-level resources** (e.g. decks): every `select` / `update` / `delete` must include `eq(decks.clerkUserId, userId)` (and the same for inserts—set `clerkUserId` from the session, not from the client).

- **Nested resources** (e.g. cards under a deck): ensure the parent deck belongs to the user before touching the child—e.g. join or subquery on `decks` with `eq(decks.clerkUserId, userId)`, or fetch the deck by `id` **and** `clerkUserId` first; if no row, return **404** (not 403 leaking existence) unless the product explicitly distinguishes them.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — any signed-in user can pass any deck id
await db.select().from(decks).where(eq(decks.id, deckIdFromClient));

// ✅ GOOD — deck must belong to this user
await db
  .select()
  .from(decks)
  .where(and(eq(decks.id, deckIdFromClient), eq(decks.clerkUserId, userId)));
```

- Do not expose other users’ primary keys or content through APIs, Server Actions, or Route Handlers. **List endpoints** must filter by `clerkUserId` (or equivalent) by default.

## Client components

- Client UI may show or hide navigation, but **enforcement lives on the server**. Never rely on hiding links or “secret” UUIDs as security.
